# Mojo FFI And Host Boundary Safety

## Ownership and lifetimes

- Document who owns buffers passed across Mojo ↔ Python/C++.
- Do not return pointers/handles to stack or temporaries across the boundary.
- Prefer copying or explicit lifetime contract over "it worked once in a test".
- After host calls into Mojo, assume host may retain references — design APIs accordingly.

## Typed boundary

- Convert wire/host primitives to domain types **at the boundary**, not deep inside kernel code.
- Do not leak raw indices/handles into public Python API when opaque ids exist.

## Errors

- Do not swallow FFI failures silently — log and return explicit error to host (exception, error code, Result).
- See **silent-exit-must-log** for paths that return without outward signal.

## GIL / threading (Python host)

- If calling from Python threads, document whether Mojo entrypoints are re-entrant and whether GIL rules apply.
- No hidden global mutable state in kernel without explicit sync story.

## Protected changes

Changing FFI function signatures or ABI layout requires explicit user approval — see **changes-and-proposals**.
